         <div type="entry">
                <head>Shemʿun Quqoyo</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Shemun-Quqoyo</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/515</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">506</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="377"/>
                    <idno type="althead">Simeon the Potter</idno>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/37</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Author of nine short poems on the Nativity.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">Simeon the Potter (5th/6th <abbr>cent.</abbr>) [<abbr>Syr. Orth.</abbr>].</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Author of nine short poems on the Nativity. When <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Yaqub-of-Serugh">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/42">Yaʿqub of
                            Serugh</persName>
                        </ref> came across him working as a potter (<hi rend="italic">quqoyo</hi>) in Geshir, a village in north Syria, he soon recognized
                        his poetic talents. Imitations of his poems gave rise to a specific genre of
                        poems, designated ‘<hi rend="italic">quqoye</hi>’.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="bibl">
                    <head>Sources</head>
                    <listBibl>
                        <bibl>S. P.  Brock, <title rend="italic">Bride of Light. Hymns on Mary
                                from the Syriac Churches</title> (Moran Etho 6; 1994), 102–8.
                            (<abbr>ET</abbr>)</bibl>
                        <bibl>S. Euringer, in <title rend="italic">
                                <abbr>OC</abbr>
                            </title> II.3 (1913), 221–35.
                            (Syr. with <abbr>GT</abbr>)</bibl>
                    </listBibl>
                </div>
